</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><bold>Brahui</bold><extension extension_name='ref' name="University of Balochistan"></extension><space/><template><target>IPAc-en</target><arg>b</arg><arg>r</arg><arg>ə</arg><arg>ˈ</arg><arg>h</arg><arg>uː</arg><arg>i</arg></template><extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>OED</target><arg>Brahui</arg></template></extension><space/>(Brahui: ) is a<space/><link><target>Dravidian language</target></link><space/>spoken by the<space/><link><target>Brahui people</target></link><space/>in the central<space/><link><target>Balochistan</target></link><space/>region of<space/><link><target>Pakistan</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Afghanistan</target></link>, and by expatriate Brahui communities in<space/><link><target>Qatar</target></link>,<space/><link><target>United Arab Emirates</target></link>,<space/><link><target>Iraq</target></link>, and<space/><link><target>Iran</target></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='https://books.google.nl/books?id=bCkaAQAAIAAJ&amp;amp;q=brahui+language+gulf+states&amp;amp;dq=brahui+language+gulf+states&amp;amp;hl=nl&amp;amp;sa=X&amp;amp;ei=PbCVVZSpJoO9ygPxw4SwCg&amp;amp;ved=0CEkQ6AEwCA'>&quot;International Journal of Dravidian Linguistics, Volumes 36-37&quot;</link><space/>department of linguistics, University of Kerala</extension><space/>It is isolated from the nearest Dravidian-speaking neighbour population of<space/><link><target>South India</target></link><space/>by a distance of more than<space/><template><target>convert</target><arg>1500</arg><arg>km</arg></template>.<extension extension_name='ref' name="Parkin37"><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Parkin</arg><arg>1989</arg><arg name="p">37</arg></template></extension><space/><link><target>Kalat District</target><part>Kalat</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Mastung District</target><part>Mastung</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Khuzdar District</target><part>Khuzdar</part></link><space/>districts of Balochistan are predominantly Brahui-speaking.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Distribution</heading><paragraph>Brahui is spoken in the central part of Pakistani Balochistan, mainly in<space/><link><target>Kalat District</target><part>Kalat</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Mastung District</target><part>Mastung</part></link>, and<space/><link><target>Khuzdar District</target><part>Khuzdar</part></link><space/>districts but also in smaller numbers in neighboring districts, as well as in<space/><link><target>Afghanistan</target></link><space/>which borders Pakistani Balochistan; however, many members of the ethnic group<space/><link><target>language attrition</target><part>no longer speak</part></link><space/>Brahui.<extension extension_name='ref' name="Parkin37"></extension><space/>The 2013 edition of<space/><link><target>Ethnologue</target></link><space/>reports that there are some 4 million speakers. Nearly all live in Pakistan, mainly in the province of Balochistan.<extension extension_name='ref' name="e18"></extension><space/>There are also an unknown very small number of expatriate Brahuis in the Arab States of the<space/><link><target>Persian Gulf</target></link>, Iranian Balochistan, and Turkmenistan.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='https://books.google.nl/books?id=bCkaAQAAIAAJ&amp;amp;q=brahui+language+gulf+states&amp;amp;dq=brahui+language+gulf+states&amp;amp;hl=nl&amp;amp;sa=X&amp;amp;ei=PbCVVZSpJoO9ygPxw4SwCg&amp;amp;ved=0CEkQ6AEwCA'>&quot;International Journal of Dravidian Linguistics, Volumes 36-37&quot;</link><space/>department of linguistics, University of Kerala</extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>Classification</heading><paragraph>Brahui belongs, with<space/><link><target>Kurukh language</target><part>Kurukh</part></link><space/>(Oraon) and<space/><link><target>Malto language</target><part>Malto</part></link>, to the northern subfamily of the Dravidian family of languages. It has been influenced by the<space/><link><target>Iranian languages</target></link><space/>spoken in the area, especially<space/><link><target>Balochi language</target><part>Balochi</part></link>.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Emeneau</arg><arg>1962</arg></template></extension><template><target>Page needed</target><arg name="date">September 2010</arg></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Dialects</heading><paragraph>There are no important dialectical differences. Jhalawani (southern, centered on<space/><link><target>Khuzdar</target></link>) and Sarawani (northern, centered on<space/><link><target>Kalat, Pakistan</target><part>Kalat</part></link>) dialects are distinguished by the pronunciation of *h, which is only retained in the north. (Elfenbein 1997)</paragraph><heading level='2'>Phonology</heading><paragraph>The vowels are the same as Balochi: long<space/><italics>a e i o u</italics>, short<space/><italics>a i u</italics>, diphthongs<space/><italics>aj, aw</italics>. Stress has also been borrowed from Balochi, and occurs on the first long vowel or diphthong, or on the first syllable if all vowels are short.</paragraph><paragraph>Consonants are also very similar to those of Balochi, but Brahui has more fricatives and nasals (Elfenbein 1993).</paragraph><table class="wikitable" style="text-align: center"><tablerow><tablehead></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Labial consonant</target><part>Labial</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Dental consonant</target><part>Dental</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Alveolar consonant</target><part>Alveolar</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Retroflex consonant</target><part>Retroflex</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Palatoalveolar consonant</target><part>Palatoalveolar</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Palatal consonant</target><part>Palatal</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Velar consonant</target><part>Velar</part></link></tablehead><tablehead><link><target>Glottal consonant</target><part>Glottal</part></link></tablehead></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Stop consonant</target><part>Stop</part></link></tablehead><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>p b</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>t d</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ʈ ɖ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>k ɡ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ʔ</arg></template></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Affricate consonant</target><part>Affricate</part></link></tablehead><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>t͡ʃ d͡ʒ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Fricative consonant</target><part>Fricative</part></link></tablehead><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>f</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>s z</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ʃ ʒ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>x ɣ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>h</arg></template></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Trill consonant</target><part>Tap</part></link></tablehead><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ɾ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ɽ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Nasal stop</target><part>Nasal</part></link></tablehead><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>m</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>n</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>ɳ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell>(<template><target>IPA</target><arg>ŋ</arg></template>)</tablecell><tablecell></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Lateral consonant</target><part>Lateral</part></link></tablehead><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>l ɬ</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell></tablerow><tablerow><tablehead><link><target>Semivowel</target></link></tablehead><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>w</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell><template><target>IPA</target><arg>j</arg></template></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell><tablecell></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Orthography</heading><paragraph>Brahui is the only<space/><link><target>Dravidian languages</target><part>Dravidian language</part></link><space/>which has not been written in a<space/><link><target>Brahmic family of scripts</target><part>Brahmi</part></link>-based script; instead, it is written in the<space/><link><target>Arabic script</target></link><space/>since the second half of the 20th century.<extension extension_name='ref'>http://www.worklib.ru/dic/%D0%B1%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B3%D1%83%D0%B8/ &quot; .&quot;</extension><space/>More recently, a Roman-based orthography named<space/><link><target>Brolikva</target></link><space/>(an abbreviation of<space/><italics>Brahui Roman Likvar</italics>) was developed by the Brahui Language Board of the<space/><link><target>University of Balochistan</target></link><space/>in Quetta, and adopted by the newspaper<space/><link><target>Talr</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>Below is the new promoted Brhu Bgal Brolikva orthography:<extension extension_name='ref' name="University of Balochistan"><template><target>citation</target><arg name="publisher">Brahui Language Board, University of Balochistan</arg><arg name="publication-place">Quetta</arg><arg name="url">https://sites.google.com/site/brahuilb/home</arg><arg name="title">Bráhuí Báşágal</arg><arg name="date">April 2009</arg><arg name="accessdate">2010-06-29</arg></template></extension></paragraph><table class="wikitable" style="font-size: 110%;"><tablerow><tablecell><link><target>b</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>p</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>s</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>y</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>v</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>x</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>e</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>z</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>f</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>m</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>n</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>l</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>g</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>c</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>t</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>r</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>d</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>o</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>h</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>j</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>k</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>a</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>i</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target>u</target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell><tablecell><link><target></target></link></tablecell></tablerow></table><paragraph>The letters with diacritics are the long vowels, post-alveolar and retroflex consonants, the voiced velar fricative and the voiceless lateral fricative.</paragraph><heading level='2'>Endangerment</heading><paragraph><template><target>See also</target><arg>List of endangered languages in Asia</arg></template>According to a 2009<space/><link><target>UNESCO</target></link><space/>report, Brahui is one of the 27<space/><link><target>languages of Pakistan</target></link><space/>that are facing the<space/><link><target>endangered language</target><part>danger</part></link><space/>of<space/><link><target>extinct language</target><part>extinction</part></link>. They classify it in &quot;unsafe&quot; status, the least endangered level out of the five levels of concern (Unsafe, Definitely Endangered, Severely Endangered, Critically Endangered, and Extinct).<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Moseley</arg><arg>2009</arg></template></extension></paragraph><heading level='3'>Publications</heading><paragraph><link><target>Talr</target></link><space/>is the first daily newspaper in the Brahui language. It uses the new Roman orthography, and is &quot;an attempt to standardize and develop [the] Brahui language to meet the requirements of modern political, social and scientific discourse.&quot;<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>citation</target><arg name="url">http://www.talarpub.tk/</arg><arg name="publisher">Talár Publications</arg><arg name="title">Haftaí Talár</arg><arg name="accessdate">2010-06-29</arg></template></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>History</heading><paragraph>There is no consensus as to whether Brahui is a relatively recent language introduced into Balochistan or remnant of an older widespread Dravidian language family. Some scholars see it as a recent migrant language to its present region. They postulate, that Brahui could only have migrated to Balochistan from<space/><link><target>central India</target></link><space/>after 1000 CE. The absence of any older Iranian (Avestan) loanwords in Brahui supports this hypothesis. The main Iranian contributor to Brahui vocabulary, Balochi, is a<space/><link><target>Northwestern Iranian language</target></link>, and moved to the area from the west only around 1000 CE.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Witzel</arg><arg>1998</arg><arg name="p">1</arg></template>, which cites<space/><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Elfenbein</arg><arg>1987</arg></template></extension><space/>One scholar places the migration s late as the 13th or 14th century.<extension extension_name='ref'><template><target>harvnb</target><arg>Sergent</arg><arg>1997</arg><arg name="pp">129–130</arg></template></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'>Notes and references</heading><paragraph><template><target>Reflist</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>Bibliography</heading><paragraph><template><target>refbegin</target></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="title">South Asian Language Resource Center Workshop on Languages of Afghanistan and neighboring areas</arg><arg name="date">December 2003</arg><arg name="chapter">Brahui - Notes</arg><arg name="first">Elena</arg><arg name="last">Bashir</arg><arg name="url">http://salrc.uchicago.edu/workshops/sponsored/121203/resources/brahui.pdf</arg><arg name="accessdate">2010-06-29</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="first">J. H.</arg><arg name="last">Elfenbein</arg><arg name="title">A Periplus of the 'Brahui Problem'</arg><arg name="journal">Studia Iranica</arg><arg name="volume">16</arg><arg name="issue">2</arg><arg name="year">1987</arg><arg name="pages">215–233</arg><arg name="doi">10.2143/SI.16.2.2014604</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="last">Emeneau</arg><arg name="first">Murray B.</arg><arg name="authorlink">Murray Barnson Emeneau</arg><arg name="year">1962</arg><arg name="title">Bilingualism and structural borrowing</arg><arg name="journal">Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society</arg><arg name="volume">106</arg><arg name="issue">5</arg><arg name="pages">430–442</arg><arg name="jstor">985488</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="title">Interactive Atlas of the World's Languages in Danger</arg><arg name="year">2009</arg><arg name="publisher">UNESCO</arg><arg name="editor-first">Christopher</arg><arg name="editor-last">Moseley</arg><arg name="url">http://www.unesco.org/culture/ich/index.php?pg</arg><arg name="oclc">435877932</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="first">Robert</arg><arg name="last">Parkin</arg><arg name="journal">Indo-Iranian Journal</arg><arg name="doi">10.1007/BF00182435</arg><arg name="pages">37–43</arg><arg name="title">Some comments on Brahui kinship terminology</arg><arg name="volume">32</arg><arg name="issue">1</arg><arg name="year">1989</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="last">Sergent</arg><arg name="first">Bernard</arg><arg name="authorlink">Bernard Sergent</arg><arg name="title">Genèse de l'Inde</arg><arg name="publisher"><space/>Bibliothèque scientifique Payot</arg><arg name="year">1997</arg><arg name="isbn">9782228891165</arg><arg name="oclc">38198091</arg></template></listitem><listitem><template><target>Citation</target><arg name="last">Witzel</arg><arg name="first">Michael</arg><arg name="authorlink">Michael Witzel</arg><arg name="date">February 1998</arg><arg name="chapter">The Languages of Harappa</arg><arg name="url">http://www.people.fas.harvard.edu/~witzel/IndusLang.pdf</arg><arg name="title">Proceedings of the Conference on the Indus Civilisation</arg><arg name="editor-last">Kenoyer</arg><arg name="editor-first">Jonathan Mark</arg><arg name="publication-place">Madison, Wisconsin</arg></template></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>refend</target></template></paragraph><heading level='2'>External links</heading><paragraph><template><target>Incubator</target><arg name="code"><space/>brh</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.ijunoon.com/Brahui/'>Online Brahui Dictionary</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://books.google.com/books?id=mrcOAAAAQAAJ&amp;amp;printsec=frontcover&amp;amp;source=gbs_ge_summary_r&amp;amp;cad=0#v=onepage&amp;amp;q&amp;amp;f=false'>''Handbook of the Birouhi language'' By Allh Baksh (1877)</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='https://sites.google.com/site/brahuilb/home'>Brahui Language Board</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='https://sites.google.com/site/brahuilb/videos-1/untitledpost'>Brhu Bgal (Brahui Alphabet)</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.lmp.ucla.edu/Profile.aspx?LangID=207&amp;amp;menu=004'>Profile of the Brahui language</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.southasiabibliography.de/Bibliography/Dravidian/Brahui___Birouhi/brahui___birouhi.html'>Partial bibliography of scholarly works on Brahui</link></listitem><listitem><link type='external' href='http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/77229/Brahui-langua